      <hedline>
        <hl1>Truth in Advertising Is Good for Judges, Too</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Marcos D Jimenez (Dade County Bar Assn) says improper judicial campaign practices shake public faith in an impartial and competent judiciary (Aug 23 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As chairman of the Dade County Bar Association's Judicial Campaign Practices Commission, I applaud your decision to report on the growing problem of judicial campaign abuse (front page, Aug. 23). The Dade County Bar Association formed the commission in 1986 to create a forum for grievances regarding mudslinging, false advertising and other campaign violations.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As chairman of the Dade County Bar Association's Judicial Campaign Practices Commission, I applaud your decision to report on the growing problem of judicial campaign abuse (front page, Aug. 23). The Dade County Bar Association formed the commission in 1986 to create a forum for grievances regarding mudslinging, false advertising and other campaign violations.</p>
        <p>Since 1998, Dade County judicial candidates have been asked to sign a pledge to conduct their campaigns with dignity. When violations of the pledge are published, this informs the voting public and acts as a deterrent. Improper judicial campaign practices shake the public's faith in an impartial and competent judiciary. Judicial campaign violators must be called to account for their actions.</p>
        <p>MARCOS D. JIMENEZ  Miami, Aug. 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
